Title: The Seven Deaths of Evelyn Hardcastle
Author: Stuart Turton
My Review: One of the best books I have read this year. The premise was so interesting, and the story was well executed. It was a great combination of twists I didn’t see coming as well as story lines I could theorize about and figure out. There were two small drawbacks for me... I felt that the beginning was a bit slow, given that the audience knows more than the protagonists, and the main character repeated himself a lot, but those were so minor relative to the complexity that I’m willing to forgive. A great book... read it with my boyfriend and we really enjoyed sharing our theories with each other as the story progressed. Definitely would recommend!

My Review: 4.5 stars! Well-written characters and fantastic world building. Took off a half a star because of the way they set up the sequel—some of the story lines were so obviously obscured so that they could be delayed, and it started to rub me the wrong way. However, I’m definitely going to continue the series, so maybe the tactic worked! Definitely would recommend.

Title: The Map of Salt and Stars
Author: Zeyn Joukhadar
My Review: If I could give this book 3.5 stars, I would. The writing is absolutely beautiful, but like others, The characters fell just a bit flat to me. They didn’t have the same personality the author imbued into the setting, and for that reason, it seemed a bit mismatched. In addition, the story seemed so fantastical but sputtered out just a bit at the end. I wouldn’t tell anyone to avoid it, but I wouldn’t necessarily recommend it either.

Title: The Calculating Stars (Lady Astronaut Universe #1)
Author: Mary Robinette Kowal
My Review: Where do I even start? I was looking forward to this book, and it was a huge disappointment. The biggest issue was the main character, Dr. Elma York. I wanted to root for her so bad, but she was immature, mean spirited, and flat out annoying. The second red flag was the absurd amount of rocket sex jokes. They were terrible, terrible puns, and the smutty scenes detracted from what little I was enjoying the story line. The writing was also bad, but not even close to the biggest problem. I will definitely not be recommending the book nor continuing the series. Hugely, hugely disappointed.

Title: The Penelopiad: The Myth of Penelope and Odysseus
Author: Margaret Atwood

Title: No Exit
Author: Taylor  Adams
My Review: Very mild spoilers ahead! I was disappointed in this book. I thought it would be more murder-mystery, but the perpetrators are discovered about 30% in and the rest of the time is more like an action thriller than anything else. The book was both predictable and unrealistic... things kept happening that just made me roll my eyes. The premise was great, but the story was poorly executed, and not very well written. There was potential there, but it needs some work.

Title: The Queen of Hearts
Author: Kimmery Martin
My Review: UGH. This book! I wanted to read about two strong female physicians, but ultimately, the characters completely ruined this book for me. I would not want to be friends with either woman or have them be my doctors. They were unprofessional, arrogant about everything, and incredibly catty—fat shaming, poor shaming, mom shaming, you name it, they did it. The story was 1/3 season one of Grey’s Anatomy, and the writing was clunky and too full of medical terms and analogies in weird places. The only redeeming characteristic was the cover—please, do yourself a favor. Look at the beautiful art work and MOVE ON.

My Review: I had a very difficult time reading this book. I’ve read several other presidential and political biographies (even another McKinley book) and really enjoyed them, so I don’t believe it’s an issue with the subject matter. The writing was slow and it was hard to really engage with the content. Sad to say this because I know there’s so much work that went into the book, but it was definitely not one of my favorites.

Title: Everything I Never Told You
Author: Celeste Ng
My Review: I began this book because of how much I liked Little Fires Everywhere, and unfortunately, it doesn’t compare. The characters were all flatter and the story seemed to drag on more. It’s still a good book, but the second half was especially slow. For me, most of the character development happens in the first half and you’re left hanging for the remainder. If I were going to recommend only one of Celeste Ng’s books, I’d recommend Little Fires.

Title: Where'd You Go, Bernadette
Author: Maria Semple
My Review: I started this book a bit hesitant—after all, the movie is coming out, and I worry that books with movies attached to them are over-rated and can’t possibly be that good. Happy to say I was wrong! The characters all had such big personalities and the writing was super witty. Kathleen Wilhoite did an amazing job narrating. Some of the dialogue was just a bit mean some times, so I’d give this 4.5 stars if I could, but over all a wonderful read.

Title: Truevine: Two Brothers, a Kidnapping, and a Mother's Quest: A True Story of the Jim Crow South
Author: Beth Macy
My Review: The story of the Muse brothers should have been captivating—unfortunately, it was poorly executed. Other reviews have mentioned that this book grew from a series of articles, and I agree that format is a better fit. There were lots of interesting sidebars but the story that should have tied them together was lost in the extra details. Ultimately, I think this book was just too long. I would give 2.5 stars, but I’ll round up to 3 just for George and Willie.

Title: Uncommon Type: Some Stories
Author: Tom Hanks
My Review: In a perfect world, I’d give this a three and a half. The characters were great, but the stories were just a bit lacking. Would not listen as an audiobook... Tom Hanks is a great narrator, but the short stories make it super choppy.

Title: The Flight Attendant
Author: Chris Bohjalian
Additional Authors: Erin Spencer, Grace Experience, Mark Deakins
My Review: It took me a long time to realize I wasn’t enjoying this book, but when it finally hit me, it really hit me. It was a slow moving plot but the worst part was the one-dimensional characters. It seemed as if they were reacting situations in stereotypical manner, every time. The writing was also super repetitive, and would repeat phrases over and over and over again. Would not recommend.

Title: The Theory That Would Not Die: How Bayes' Rule Cracked the Enigma Code, Hunted Down Russian Submarines, and Emerged Triumphant from Two Centuries of Controversy
Author: Sharon Bertsch McGrayne

Title: A Ladder to the Sky
Author: John Boyne
Additional Authors: Richard E. Grant, Robert Cordery, Nina Sosanya, Laurence Kennedy
My Review:
Oh, WOW. I had a very complicated relationship with this book. I read The Heart’s Invisible Furies last year, and was really looking forward to reading more of John Boyne.

That being said, I did not like this book. I didn’t enjoy the read. However, I also don’t think it’s a bad story—rather, Boyne tells the story so well that you’re left with a mix of pity and revulsion for almost all of the major characters. You spend the entire book waiting for the new and terrible things that will inevitably come at you. I hated, HATED Maurice Swift. He was awful. But was the writing bad if the book makes you feel powerful, albeit negative emotions?

Ultimately, I don’t think I can truly judge the book of what I felt about it. If I were giving it stars based on how the characters made me feel, it would be a one star review. If I were giving it stars based on how deeply it made me feel those feelings, I’d give it five. I’m settling in the middle at three. Others may like it better than me, and I might even recommend it—just be prepared.

Title: A Darker Shade of Magic (Shades of Magic, #1)
Author: Victoria E. Schwab
My Review:
I hate to give this book such a low rating (low for me, anyway), but I’ve come to the conclusion that it just wasn’t for me. The premise and setting were intriguing, but I consistently had a hard time really digging my teeth into the book. I can’t say if that’s because portions of the storyline felt tedious, or because the narrator of the audiobook was a bit monotonous, or what.

I wouldn’t not recommend it—there’s definitely a good chance someone different would like it more than I did.

Title: The Fellowship of the Ring (The Lord of the Rings, #1)
Author: J.R.R. Tolkien

Title: An Anonymous Girl
Author: Greer Hendricks
My Review: This book was really, really great. Unfortunately, I don’t know if I could wholeheartedly recommend An Anonymous Girl to everyone, especially my male friends. It’s a just a little too girly...for example, one of the main characters is a makeup artist and the clothes get discussed more than usual. BUT. The two authors/back and forth writing style is super unique, and I think the premise of the psychological experiment is fascinating. The detail is really great also, it’s just unfortunate that some of the details that set the scenes so brilliantly might put other people off.

Author: Kate  Moore
Publisher: HighBridge, a Division of Recorded Books
My Review: This book was very interesting, but I wasn't as happy with the writing style as I could have been. I felt as though the book and research were mostly focused on the Ottawa plant, but that isn't what the story started with. I would have also been glad to hear more details of the lasting effects, such as the establishment of OSHA and the scientific research based on the girls. Finally, I listened to an audio version of the book and it may have helped to actually read it--the narrator was not my favorite, but not terrible either. All in all, I would recommend it to others, but it might not be my first recommendation.

Title: A Fall of Marigolds
Author: Susan Meissner
My Review: I’ve read other books by Susan Meissner and I was really excited for this one, but the end of the story disappointed me. The writing was decent, but some phrases were a little tiresome after hearing them several times. This book is also split between two stories, but the dominant one got to be a bit much and I wish the distribution had been more even... I was much more interested in the present day events. Regardless, this was an engaging read and I did find myself wanting to know what was going to happen next in the story... would definitely recommend more of this author, even if it’s not this particular book.
